comments.text:
In a way I really miss what Slender used to be in 2012-13 rather than it 
now being reduced to a mass of fan-games with no official comeback in 
sight. Five Nights At Freddys is a great game series don't get me wrong, I 
love the story and find so much intrigue and mystery in it, but is it 
scary? Ha, NO! The same thing can be seen in pretty much all the games. An 
animatronic jumpscares someone and they go "Damnit, I was so close. Oh 
well, better try again" instead of "AAAHHHHH!!! God....ughh that gave me a 
f**king heart attack!". It has a great story behind it, but is not even 
close to being scary, with the tension always making up for it. Slender was 
consistently scary, with the free ability to roam giving more fear to 
buildup, as Slender Man would actively pursue you, the game ambience and 
sound effects contributing to the horror. And your lack of any form of 
deterrent to him adds to this. I really hope that when the Five Nighrts At 
Freddys movie is out, that is it. There is no fourth game, and the story is 
closed with theorists such as myself still able to ask questions and come 
up with ideas every now and then. That would be the perfect time for 
Slender to make one hell of a return to the horror gaming genre!﻿
comments.author: Patrick Fisher

comments.text:
+Patrick Fisher FNaF is a novelty scare. That first time playing was really 
terrifying. If you watched Mark play it first before you played it you 
might have seriously ruined it. That first playthrough was the most 
terrifying game ever. But after Night 2 it gets old... very very quickly. 
Mark would probably agree, before you see everything it's scary. After? 
Meh. That's what a novelty scare is, Amnesia The Dark Decent... no matter 
how many times I play it or watch someone play it that game gets me every 
time. Like Silent Hill 2 they never get old. That's the difference between 
truly horrifying and novelty scares.

comments.author: An Ostrich

comments.text:
+Patrick Fisher Having only been a viewer of lets plays and never an active 
player of either Slender OR FNAF, I have to say that watching someone play 
it has a similar effect on me as it does the player. Really, I can disagree 
with NONE of what you have said, and it's not only disappointing to see no 
LEGITIMATE expansion of Slender in sight, but it's almost scary (ironic, 
isn't it?). The horror industry of video games seems to be mainly (though 
not anywhere near completely) relying on the small-name, Source Engine 
material, and to see a whole genre that was once ruled by Resident Evil and 
Dead Island get reduced to such obscurity. Games like The Last Of Us have 
helped keep horror gaming alive, but for how long? I agree with you; 
Slender could be the Batman of gaming right now, if it tried. The game we 
need.
